<p><img src="/imgs/jekyllrb.png#noshadow" alt="jekyll" /></p>

<p><a href="https://jekyllrb.com/">Jekyll</a> is a static site generator. You can install it on your Windows or Linux pc or MacOS. It might seem tricky at first, but Iâ€™ll tell you exactly what to do.</p>

<h3 id="prerequisites">Prerequisites</h3>

<p>Before you install Jekyll you have to make sure that some tools are already installed on your pc. To do that, you need to <strong>open the shell (Terminal)</strong> and then follow the instructions you can find on <a href="https://jekyllrb.com/docs/installation/">this page</a>.</p>

<p>If something is missing, you can download and install it from:</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong><a href="https://www.ruby-lang.org/en/downloads/">Ruby</a></strong></li>
  <li><strong><a href="https://rubygems.org/pages/download">RubyGems</a></strong></li>
  <li><strong><a href="https://gcc.gnu.org/install/">GCC</a></strong></li>
  <li><strong><a href="https://www.gnu.org/software/make/">Make</a></strong></li>
</ul>

<h3 id="install-jekyll">Install Jekyll</h3>

<p>When you have everything you need, you may proceed with the installation of Jekyll and bundler gems.</p>

<p>Write on your terminal:</p>

<p><img src="/imgs/how-to-7.png" alt="install jekyll and bundler gems" /></p>

<p>Now, you can <a href="/docs/set-up-lilium.md">download and install Lilium Digital Garden</a> and start your first Jekyll site using this template.</p>
